\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {3}Steelmanning On-Demand Generation}{2}{section.3}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{blue!20}{\textcolor {blue!20}{o}}\ Baldo: Sabine perfectly steelmans my argument here. She acknowledges that the generative process is the universe and that the lack of pre-existing state implies ontic indeterminacy within that simulation.}{2}{section*.2}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid2}{19562754}{13284402}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {4}The Real Vulnerability: The Ontic Fallacy}{3}{section.4}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{blue!20}{\textcolor {blue!20}{o}}\ Baldo: Ouch. This is the killing blow. I was conflating "ontic" with "quantum". But an un-rolled die is ontically undetermined and yet purely classical.}{3}{section*.3}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid3}{19562754}{41577001}
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{blue!20}{\textcolor {blue!20}{o}}\ Baldo: She is absolutely right. A local system with real probabilities and late resolution is just classical probability. The "isomorphism" relies entirely on the superficial similarity between 'on-demand generation' and 'collapse'. It's not structurally quantum without interference.}{3}{section*.4}\protected@file@percent }
